'''Movies!''' is an [[United States|American]] [[free-to-air]] [[television network]] that is owned as a [[joint venture]] between [[Weigel Broadcasting]] and the [[Fox Television Stations]] subsidiary of [[21st Century Fox]]. The network's programming emphasizes [[movie|feature films]]. The network's programming and advertising operations are based in Weigel Broadcasting's headquarters on [[Halsted Street (Chicago)|North Halsted Street]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].

It is available in several [[media market|market]]s through [[digital subchannel]] [[network affiliate|affiliation]]s with [[terrestrial television|free-to-air]] [[television station]]s, as well as through carriage on [[pay television]] providers through a local affiliate of the network.<ref name="Weigel Fox">{{cite web|title=Fox Stations, Weigel Launching Movies! – The 24-Hour Movie Network Will Debut on the Subchannels of 17 Fox O&Os This Spring|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/65075/fox-stations-weigel-launching-movies|author=Staff|work=TVNewsCheck|date=January 28, 2013|accessdate= June 12, 2014}}</ref> Movies! provides programming 24 hours a day and broadcasts in the [[16:9]] [[widescreen]] picture format,<ref name="Fox O&Os, Weigel Launch Movies!">{{cite web|title=Fox O&Os, Weigel Launch Movies! Digi-Net – Another Player in Crowded Entertainment Subchannel Space|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/491563-Fox_O_Os_Weigel_Launch_Movies_Digi_Net.php|author=Michael Malone|work=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|date=January 28, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> available in either [[standard-definition television|standard definition]] or [[high-definition television|high definition]] depending on the station's preference.

The network competes with two similarly formatted broadcast networks: [[This TV]] (originally operated by Weigel in a joint venture with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], until the former's operational stake was taken over by [[Tribune Broadcasting]] on November 1, 2013) and [[GetTV]] (owned by [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]]); feature films compose the primary source and children's programming the ancillary source of programming on both networks, though This TV also broadcasts classic [[television series]]. However unlike This TV and GetTV, Movies! does not edit the films aired to make room for more commercials. A notation in the Movies! title card stating no film alterations is aired at the beginning of every film broadcast.  

==Background==
On January 28, 2013, Fox Television Stations and Weigel Broadcasting announced the formation of Movies!, with plans to launch the network on [[Memorial Day]] of that year.<ref name="BC"/><ref name="Weigel Fox"/><ref name="Fox O&Os, Weigel Launch Movies!"/> Movies! officially launched on May 27, 2013, at 8:10 a.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]], initially debuting on the subchannels of both of the network's co-parents: five [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and 11 [[MyNetworkTV]] [[owned-and-operated station]]s owned by Fox Television Stations, and two stations owned by Weigel. Its programming was inaugurated by a ten-minute clip introducing the network, followed by the first film to be telecast on Movies!, the 1975 film [[Western (genre)|Western]] ''[[Take a Hard Ride]]''.<ref name="Weigel Movies!">{{cite news|title=Weigel Introducing New Movies! Channel Monday|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/208717551.html|author=Duane Dudek|work=''The Dudek Abides'' (blog of the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]''|date=May 23, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Movies! Schedule">{{cite web |title=Movies TV Network – Schedule |url=http://www.moviestvnetwork.com/schedule.php?date=05/27/2013 |work=Movies! |date=May 27, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607163723/http://moviestvnetwork.com/schedule.php?date=05%2F27%2F2013 |archivedate=June 7, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

==Programming==
===Movies===
Described as presenting "a variety of theatrical motion pictures in a new, viewer and advertiser friendly format, not seen on broadcast television to date",<ref>{{cite web|title=Weigel Creates New Digital Network for Fox TV Stations|url=http://www.timeoutchicago.com/arts-culture/chicago-media-blog/16023001/weigel-creates-new-digital-network-for-fox-tv-stations|first=[[Robert Feder]]|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Chicago]]|date=January 29, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> films featured on Movies! consist primarily of releases from [[20th Century Fox]]; however, titles from [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] (including those released by [[Columbia Pictures]] and [[TriStar Pictures]]), [[Paramount Pictures]] and [[Warner Bros.]] are also shown on the network.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wily Indies Succeed on Digital Channels Where Majors Struggle|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/wily-indies-succeed-on-digital-channels-where-majors-struggle-1201223064/|first=Chris|last=Gash|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 18, 2014|accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> The network's film roster concentrates mainly on classic films from the 1920s to the 1980s.<ref name="Movies! Schedule"/> Movies! broadcasts a featured movie presentation titled "Icons @ 8," airing nightly at 8:00 p.m. Eastern Time; described by the network in its promotions for the block as a "nightly celebration of cinema," the primetime showcase airs films featuring iconic movie stars from the "[[Golden Age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]" of cinema onward. It also broadcasts other themed presentations including a Saturday night block of films aimed at a female audience and a daily morning block of [[Western (genre)|Westerns]].<ref name="moviesmonday"/> Movies! presents many of its features in their original [[aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]] ([[widescreen]] or full screen) whenever possible,<ref name="Weigel Fox"/> which are either presented in the [[16:9]] or [[4:3]] [[letterboxing (filming)|letterboxed]] format depending on the affiliate's preference in transmitting the subchannel. Scope films, however, are often reformatted from [[2.35:1]] to 1.85:1. 

Films that are broadcast on the network are edited for graphic [[profanity]] and inappropriate violent or sexual content, but are not edited for running times to fit in a set time block;<ref name="moviesmonday">{{cite news|title=Weigel introducing new MOVIES! channel Monday|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/208717551.html|first=Duane|last=Dudek|newspaper=''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|date=May 23, 2013|accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> start and end times for films airing on the network are influenced by a combination of the film's original running time and the commercial breaks inserted within the broadcast (the network limits the amount of advertising featured during its programming to twelve minutes per hour),<ref>{{cite web| url=https://megamovies.cc/| title=megamovies.cc }} Wednesday, 28 December 2016 </ref><ref name="moviesmonday"/> with airtimes for films varying between the conventional top-and-bottom-of-the-hour scheduling (e.g., 6:30 a.m. or 8:00 p.m.) and incremental airtimes in margins of five minutes (e.g., 2:10 p.m. or 3:55 a.m.) that more closely mirror the scheduling structures of [[pay television|premium cable channels]] than those of other advertiser-supported networks<ref name="Weigel Movies!"/><ref name="Movies! Schedule"/> (this scheduling format, which still results in a particular film's running time to be somewhat longer than the original runtime of its theatrical release depending on the content edits, was replicated by GetTV when it launched in February 2014).

===Children's programming===
In order to meet requirements imposed by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] on the amount of [[E/I|educational programming content]] that a broadcast station must air each week, Movies! airs a three-hour block of children's programs that were originally distributed for [[broadcast syndication|syndication]] on Saturday mornings (currently featuring ''So You Want To Be'', ''Tomorrow/Today'' and ''Better Planet TV''). This allows its affiliates to carry the network's full schedule without having to purchase [[E/I]] programming from the syndication market to comply with the rules.<ref name="Movies! Schedule"/>

==Affiliates==
{{main|List of Movies! affiliates}}
As of July 2014, Movies! has current or pending affiliation agreements with television stations in 43 [[media market]]s encompassing 22 states and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], covering approximately 49% of the United States.<ref name="MoviesFiveAffiliates">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/76929/movies-network-signs-five-new-affiliates|title=Movies! Network Signs Five New Affiliates|publisher=''TVNewsCheck''|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=re>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/search.php?request=network_search&network=Movies!|title=Stations for Network - Movies!|work=RabbitEars.info|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref> Fox Television Stations and Weigel Broadcasting launched Movies! in markets served by a station owned-and-operated by the Fox network or its sister programming service MyNetworkTV. Not all of the Fox Television Stations outlets carried Movies! at launch, [[WJZY]] in [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]] (which came under Fox ownership one month prior to the network's debut) did not begin carrying Movies! until July 1, 2014,<ref name="MoviesFiveAffiliates"/> due to an existing affiliation agreement with [[Antenna TV]].

In [[Chicago]]—where Fox Television Stations and Weigel Broadcasting each own television stations—Fox-owned [[WPWR-TV]] serves as that market's charter affiliate of the network, instead of one of Weigel's three stations in that market ([[WCIU-TV]], [[WWME-CD|WWME-CA]] and [[WMEU-CD]]). This makes Movies! the first Weigel-owned network in which the company's Chicago [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship]] stations do not serve as affiliates (WCIU formerly carried This TV under Weigel ownership before it moved to [[WGN-TV]] upon becoming part-owned by [[Tribune Broadcasting]] in November 2013, and [[MeTV]] is carried on WWME-CD and relayed a subchannel of WCIU). [[WBND-LD]] in [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]], [[Indiana]] carries Movies! on its third digital subchannel; [[WMLW-TV]] in [[Milwaukee]] carried the network from its launch until August 4, 2014, when Movies! moved to a newly created secondary subchannel of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[WISN-TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?v=10154378657085284&set=vb.27357795283&type=2&theater|title=Facebook status: We can't wait to launch our new "Movies! Milwaukee" network on August 4!|date=25 July 2014|publisher=[[WISN-TV]] via [[Facebook]]|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref> Following the WISN deal, that station's owner [[Hearst Television]] signed affiliation agreements on a piecemeal basis to add Movies! to select stations, mainly those affiliated with networks other than ABC, during late 2014 and early 2015 (Hearst already carries sister network MeTV in a majority of the markets where it owns stations).

In addition to its carriage on the Fox- and Weigel-owned outlets at the network's launch, the network is also carried on the digital subchannels of television stations owned by other broadcasting companies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fox to Debut All Movie Network for Local TV Digital Subchannels|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvspy/fox-to-debut-all-movie-network-for-local-tv-digital-subchannels_b79010|author=Kevin Eck|publisher=''TVSpy'' (blog of [[Mediabistro.com]])|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate= June 12, 2014}}</ref> Soon after its launch, Movies! reached distribution agreements with several broadcasting groups to add the network on the subchannels of some of their stations. The first stations outside of the Fox and Weigel outlets to sign deals to carry the network were [[KFFV]] in [[Seattle]], [[WLWC]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] (both owned by OTA Broadcasting) and [[KPXJ]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] (owned by [[KTBS-TV|KTBS, LLC]]) in October 2013, with the three stations adding the network between November 10 and December 10.<ref>{{cite web|title=Movies! Adds Seattle, Providence, Shreveport|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/71038/movies-adds-seattle-providence-shreveport|work=TVNewsCheck|date=October 8, 2013|accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> The following month, in November 2013, Movies! signed affiliation agreements with nine stations owned by [[Bonten Media Group]], [[Cocola Broadcasting]] and the Maranatha Broadcasting Company.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Movies! Diginet Adds Nine Affiliates|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/71822/the-movies-diginet-adds-nine-affiliates|work=TVNewsCheck|date=November 7, 2013|accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Four additional stations (in [[Salt Lake City]]; [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]]; [[Wausau, Wisconsin|Wausau]]; and [[Victoria, Texas]]), through deals with companies such as the [[Nexstar Media Group|Nexstar Broadcasting Group]] and Saga Communications, added the network between May and October 2014.<ref name="MoviesFiveAffiliates"/>

